GENDER AND BEHAVIOUR 
what is sex - biological shit 
gender - social shit - attrbutes on sex enforced by society 
there are only 2 sexes - male and female 
but there are multiple genders - males, females and fluid - have distinct set of characteristics and roles in society 
	gender can change over time 
	before in korea - tall muscular - but now males have become more feminine 
usually - patriarchal society 
muoso culture - matriarchal society 

gender roles - define how men, women should behave - depends on society 
for our society 
	women - expected to be affective (emotion driven) and communal (community oriented) - kind, gentle - housewife and mother - largely restricted to feminine occupations e.g. nurses, teachers - need to have affective and communal characteristics to be successful 
		physical attributes - waist to hip ratio 
	men - achievement-oriented, dominant - Instrumental (goal and achievement oriented) and agentic (decision makers)- often have to sacrifice interpersonal relationships to achieve these goals - independent and self relia, solve problems by yourself and never seek help - stoic, repress emotions - fearless 
		social roles - work, have own career - be successful - expected to take on leadership roles - 
		physical - tall, muscular etc
		have to be anti-feminite - avoid anything that is feminine 
gender and names - names entail parents expectations - meaning of names often different - women names more flowery, men names more masculine 
gender and growth environment - boys given different toys than girls are - this reflects the different expectations parents have of their children 
gender and career choice - young guys wanna be football players, pilots. young girls wanna become cheerleaders etc. 
	this shows how rigid our gender role expectations are 
 
gender role strain 
	have to live up to gender role expectations - if we act in accordance we will fit in easily in society 
		however, if we dont, we are excluded and attacked 
		negative consequences from gender role - gender role strain 
	applicable to both:
	intra role conflict - within one role, different expectations conflict with each other - e.g. men are expected to be successful in career and also be independent and self reliant - cant do tasks on the job that require you to seek assistance or work with others 
	inter role conflicts - when we have more than one role - e.g. women during day time have working roles, and at night they have a motherly role - these expectations may conflict - imagine boss asked you to stay overtime, then you cant take care of your kid - women face it more than men, as women have more roles than men do 
	Masculine gender role strain: 
	pressure to succeed - shame and low self esteem, sacrificing interpersonal relationships 
	surpression of emotions - to be stoic - cant express emotions to partner - difficulties in interpersonal relationships - less likely to seek help when problems arise, resort to other means to curb the pain 
	feminine gender role strain:
	underestimation of abilities: females estimate their test score to be lower - but in reality it has nothing to do with gender 
		especially in math and science - this discourages women to go for these roles 
	lower career aspirations - 
	ability achievement gap - wider in women than in men 
	juggling multiple roles - inter role conflicts - 
		men often dont do houshold tasks, and when they do they do the less urgent tasks - tasks done by the two sexes is very different - which is why women experience more stress 
	females - strain at the work place 
		access discrimination - sex is often considered implicitly when hiring decisions are made 
			most managerial positions are occupied by men - often occupations that give them a higher salary 
			females - elementary occupations and clerical support workers - lower salary and social status 
		treatment discrimination - different treatment received at work based on sex 
			glass ceiling - invisible barrier that prevents women from climbing up the ladder - often men are chosen for promotions
			glass escalator - men promoted faster than women - simply based on their sex - especially in female dominated fields e.g. nursing 
			why? men steriotyped to have better abilities 
			differential standards 
				in male dominated occupations - during evaluations women rated lower, subject to higher standards 
			pay disparity 
				women paid lower on average 
gender identity 
	your perception of who you are - are you a male or female? masculine or feminine? - I identify myself as a thinkpad 
	scores - I am undifferentiated 
	Androigynous - good at everything 
	undifferentiated - dont have a clear gender identity 

	gender identity influences stress management techniques 
		androgynous - best management 
			need flexibility - coping technique depends on stressor - 
			these people have the best of both worlds 
			this is why parents giving children both kinds of toys 
		undiffernetiated - worst management 
theories of gender identity 
	biological theory 
		nature vs nurture - by influencing persons upbringing, we can influence the gender identity 
			david reimer and john money case 
				there were twins 
				one guy had penis burned off 
				dr money - can change gender identity 
				baby essentially gender neutral for first 2 years 
				one raised as girl and one raised as boy 
				parents cant reveal truth to children - keep him convinced that he is a girl 
				when children were 7 years old, girl had very different characteristics than the twin boy 
				this shows that nurture is more important than nature 
				however, things dont go so well 
				twin brother gave brenda his toys 
				"brenda" eventually stopped acting as a girl, as she got older 
				dr money asked brenda about her gender - tried to convince her of her gender - 	
					focused on physical differences 
					showed her pictures of women giving birth 
				brenda still resistant 
				dr. money proposed additional surgery, but brenda not comfortable 
				dr. money used drastic measures - to make her understand the gender differences 
					parents unaware 
				defenders - said false memory in children 
				brenda growing as a troubled child - hard time adjusting - bullying 
				eventually threatened to kill himself 
				parents disclosed this to them 
				brenda changed gender back to male 
					not happy with assigned gender 
				shared their story 
				too much for brother - committed suicide
				brenda - faced trouble later, committed suicide as well 
			this study shows that gender identity influenced by nature - genes play a more dominant role 
			but this is just a single story 
			hormones 
				androgynes - male sex characteristics - biological 
				estrogens - female sex characteristics 
				both male and female have both - but males have more androgyns than estrogens, and vice versa for females
					psychologists say our gender identity is shaped by the proportion of these hormones  
					how do we test this ? we use experimental study - one would be exposed to more androgyns, other exposed to more estrogens 
						but are participants willing to do this? NO 
						we can make use of natural experiments - cases of people with unique features - allows us to carry out studies similar to experiments - e.g. investigate females with cowhatthefuck - the condition has females exposed to high levels of andryogens - compare these females to the normal ones 
							those with this condition cannot mestruate regularly - dont have reproductive capacity 
							voice is deeper 
							behaviours are male-like - as compared to the regular females
				psychosexual theory 
					we are born with sexual instincts 
					stages 
						phallic stage 
							3-6 years 
							boys - odeipus complex (develop sexual fantasy towards mother), castration anxiety (fear that father, who mom is with, so fantasies with mom are unacceptable) - so you adopt the identity of the person you identify with - e.g. identify with father, try to behave similarly - if father feminine then child feminine - 
								based on unconscious drive - 
