	sources of stress at work 
		individual stressors
			overload, too many responsibilities, underwork (repetitive work, boring), role conflict (spend time with family or at work),  
		group stressors 
		
		organizational stressors 
			conflicting policies, too much or too little strture (too many restrictions, too much freedom - no clear rules or boundaries - causes anxiety), racism, sexism 
		physical environment
		
	models of occupational stress 
		karasek
			physchological demands
				too much work
			decision control
				locus of control - are u in control of what happens to you at the workplace 
				high demand, low control - work hard, long hours, have little say at workplace - e.g. cashier 
			study - men in sweden 
				survey - workers to report characteristics of work in terms of psychological demand and control 
					then asked them about heart disease 
					these occur in occupations with high level of c=occupational stress and low control
		M & J 
			burnout - result of long term high stress - state of exhaustion mentally and physically 
			diagnostic criteria 	
				emotional exhaustion - Emotional exhaustion is a chronic state of physical and emotional depletion that results from excessive job and/or personal demands and continuous stress. It describes a feeling of being emotionally overextended and exhausted by one's work
				depersonalization - numbness in emotion, no sadness or happiness at work, disassociation with normal condition, quite common  
					not depression - which is a mood disorder 
				lack of personal accomplishment - no matter how successful youre at work you cannot experience joy from work - on;ly in work itself
			other warning signs discussed
			consequences discussed 
	coping with occupational stress - similar to coping with regular stress
		bargain more decision making power - to get locus of control 
